</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Magnetic resonance (MR) imaging has emerged as an imaging modality that can be used to help diagnose and evaluate Crohn disease of the small and large bowel. MR imaging has high diagnostic accuracy in the detection of Crohn disease, and high-resolution thin-section MR images can demonstrate transmural pathologic changes of Crohn disease from the level of the mucosa to that of the mesentery. High-resolution MR image data also may be used to construct high-quality multiplanar and endoluminal views that may provide additional diagnostic information. Knowledge of the MR imaging findings of Crohn disease and how they correlate with the pathologic features of the disease is important to facilitate accurate diagnosis and detect complications.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095503">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095503">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g10a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1202" aria-labelledby="f10a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Mural abscess in a patient undergoing anti–tumor necrosis factor therapy with infliximab. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.9, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows a round hyperintense lesion (arrow) in the wall of the thickened distal ileum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.3/2.5, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows a lesion with rimlike enhancement (arrow), a finding suggestive of a mural abscess. Infliximab therapy was discontinued.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f10a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g10b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1201" aria-labelledby="f10b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Mural abscess in a patient undergoing anti–tumor necrosis factor therapy with infliximab. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.9, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows a round hyperintense lesion (arrow) in the wall of the thickened distal ileum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.3/2.5, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows a lesion with rimlike enhancement (arrow), a finding suggestive of a mural abscess. Infliximab therapy was discontinued.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f10b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c11a.jpeg" height="949" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Serosal hypervascularity. <b>(a)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a nestlike formation of tortuous vessels (arrow) overlying the site of inflammation. <b>(b)</b> High-resolution sagittal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows enlarged serosal vessels (arrow). Minor bowel wall thickening, a loss of mucosal folds in the terminal ileum, and a lack of mesenteric inflammation also are seen. Chronic Crohn disease with recurrent ulcers and ileal strictures was found at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f11a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g11b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1633" aria-labelledby="f11b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Serosal hypervascularity. <b>(a)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a nestlike formation of tortuous vessels (arrow) overlying the site of inflammation. <b>(b)</b> High-resolution sagittal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows enlarged serosal vessels (arrow). Minor bowel wall thickening, a loss of mucosal folds in the terminal ileum, and a lack of mesenteric inflammation also are seen. Chronic Crohn disease with recurrent ulcers and ileal strictures was found at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f11b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g12a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1625" aria-labelledby="f12a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Sinus tracts. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows sinus tracts, which appear as linear spiculated structures (straight arrows) adjacent to the ileum. One tract has progressed to an enteroenteric fistula (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows the sites of the fistula (arrow) and sinus tracts (arrowheads). The latter appear to be adhesions with fat wrapping.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f12a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c12b.jpeg" height="984" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f12b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Sinus tracts. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows sinus tracts, which appear as linear spiculated structures (straight arrows) adjacent to the ileum. One tract has progressed to an enteroenteric fistula (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows the sites of the fistula (arrow) and sinus tracts (arrowheads). The latter appear to be adhesions with fat wrapping.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f12b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g13a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1539" aria-labelledby="f13a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Internal fistulas. <b>(13a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows inflamed distal and terminal ileum (arrows) and a contrast material–filled fistula at the ileocecal junction (arrowhead). <b>(13b)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the terminal ileum (<b>*</b>), the ileocecal junction (arrow), and the fistula (dashed line).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f13a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c13b.jpeg" height="1280" width="711" aria-labelledby="f13b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Internal fistulas. <b>(13a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows inflamed distal and terminal ileum (arrows) and a contrast material–filled fistula at the ileocecal junction (arrowhead). <b>(13b)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the terminal ileum (<b>*</b>), the ileocecal junction (arrow), and the fistula (dashed line).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f13b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g14x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1421" aria-labelledby="f14-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows a stellate enteroenteric fistula (arrow) in the mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f14-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g15x.jpeg" height="1320" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f15-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Enterocutaneous fistula. Axial true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows an enterocutaneous fistula arising from inflamed ileum and extending anteriorly to the midline and left iliac fossa (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f15-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g16a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1434" aria-labelledby="f16a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Enterovesical fistula. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 60° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows inflamed distal ileum and thickened bladder wall (arrow), findings indicative of an enterovesical fistula. <b>(b)</b> High-resolution axial true FISP MR image obtained at the level of the dome of the bladder shows air-related artifacts and a fluid level within the bladder (arrow), findings indicative of a patent fistula.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f16a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g16b.jpeg" height="1200" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f16b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Enterovesical fistula. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 60° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows inflamed distal ileum and thickened bladder wall (arrow), findings indicative of an enterovesical fistula. <b>(b)</b> High-resolution axial true FISP MR image obtained at the level of the dome of the bladder shows air-related artifacts and a fluid level within the bladder (arrow), findings indicative of a patent fistula.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f16b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g17x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1413" aria-labelledby="f17-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Abscess. Contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.3/2.5, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows an abscess with an enhancing margin (arrow) in the terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f17-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g18a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1200" aria-labelledby="f18a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Inflammatory adhesions. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows a sharp kink in the sigmoid colon (arrow) and abrupt narrowing in the distal ileum (arrowhead), findings suggestive of adhesions obstructing both segments. <b>(b)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows linear iso-intense bands (arrow) causing stretching and kinking of the small bowel and colon, findings suggestive of adhesions and adhesive bands. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows adhesions (arrow) between the ileum and the ascending colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f18a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g18b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1201" aria-labelledby="f18b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Inflammatory adhesions. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows a sharp kink in the sigmoid colon (arrow) and abrupt narrowing in the distal ileum (arrowhead), findings suggestive of adhesions obstructing both segments. <b>(b)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows linear isointense bands (arrow) causing stretching and kinking of the small bowel and colon, findings suggestive of adhesions and adhesive bands. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows adhesions (arrow) between the ileum and the ascending colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f18b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18c-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c18c.jpeg" height="854" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f18c-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span> Inflammatory adhesions. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows a sharp kink in the sigmoid colon (arrow) and abrupt narrowing in the distal ileum (arrowhead), findings suggestive of adhesions obstructing both segments. <b>(b)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) shows linear isointense bands (arrow) causing stretching and kinking of the small bowel and colon, findings suggestive of adhesions and adhesive bands. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows adhesions (arrow) between the ileum and the ascending colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f18c-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g19a.jpeg" height="1188" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f19a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Fibrotic stricture. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.1/2.5, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows an inhomogeneously enhancing stricture in the distal ileum (arrow). Areas of hypointensity within the bowel wall are indicative of fibrosis. Note the lack of edema and mesenteric inflammation. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows fibrotic strictures (arrows) separated by focal regions of dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f19a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c19b.jpeg" height="837" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f19b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Fibrotic stricture. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.1/2.5, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows an inhomogeneously enhancing stricture in the distal ileum (arrow). Areas of hypointensity within the bowel wall are indicative of fibrosis. Note the lack of edema and mesenteric inflammation. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows fibrotic strictures (arrows) separated by focal regions of dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f19b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g01a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1139" aria-labelledby="f1a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Aphthous ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3 [repetition time msec/echo time msec], 60° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) with fat suppression shows thickening and blunting of mucosal folds in the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in a plane parallel to the bowel wall, shows high-signal-intensity aphthous ulcers surrounded by a rim of edema (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Endoluminal MR image shows ulcers as round craters with a raised edematous rim. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained at colonoscopy shows aphthous ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f1a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g01b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1101" aria-labelledby="f1b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Aphthous ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3 [repetition time msec/echo time msec], 60° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) with fat suppression shows thickening and blunting of mucosal folds in the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in a plane parallel to the bowel wall, shows high-signal-intensity aphthous ulcers surrounded by a rim of edema (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Endoluminal MR image shows ulcers as round craters with a raised edematous rim. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained at colonoscopy shows aphthous ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f1b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1c-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c01c.jpeg" height="1027" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f1c-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Aphthous ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3 [repetition time msec/echo time msec], 60° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) with fat suppression shows thickening and blunting of mucosal folds in the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in a plane parallel to the bowel wall, shows high-signal-intensity aphthous ulcers surrounded by a rim of edema (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Endoluminal MR image shows ulcers as round craters with a raised edematous rim. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained at colonoscopy shows aphthous ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f1c-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1d-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c01d.jpeg" height="1280" width="1139" aria-labelledby="f1d-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span> Aphthous ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3 [repetition time msec/echo time msec], 60° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) with fat suppression shows thickening and blunting of mucosal folds in the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in a plane parallel to the bowel wall, shows high-signal-intensity aphthous ulcers surrounded by a rim of edema (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Endoluminal MR image shows ulcers as round craters with a raised edematous rim. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained at colonoscopy shows aphthous ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f1d-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f20a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g20a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1621" aria-labelledby="f20a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> Pseudosacculation. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows pseudosacculation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the shortened, fibrosed mesenteric border (arrow) and pseudosaccules on the antimesenteric border (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f20a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f20b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c20b.jpeg" height="887" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f20b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> Pseudosacculation. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows pseudosacculation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the shortened, fibrosed mesenteric border (arrow) and pseudosaccules on the antimesenteric border (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f20b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f21a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g21a.jpeg" height="1548" width="1387" aria-labelledby="f21a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Regenerative polyps in a patient with chronic Crohn disease. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows nodular filling defects in the descending colon (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×10; hematoxylin-eosin stain) from a colonic biopsy specimen shows a regenerative polyp (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f21a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f21b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c21b.jpeg" height="922" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f21b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Regenerative polyps in a patient with chronic Crohn disease. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows nodular filling defects in the descending colon (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×10; hematoxylin-eosin stain) from a colonic biopsy specimen shows a regenerative polyp (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f21b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f22a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g22a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1631" aria-labelledby="f22a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> Neoplasia in a patient with known Crohn disease who presented with bowel obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows multiple strictures (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal high-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows eccentric thickening of one of the strictures with a nodular mass (arrow) and lymph nodes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f22a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f22b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g22b.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f22b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> Neoplasia in a patient with known Crohn disease who presented with bowel obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows multiple strictures (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal high-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows eccentric thickening of one of the strictures with a nodular mass (arrow) and lymph nodes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f22b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f23a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g23a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1446" aria-labelledby="f23a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> Strictureplasty. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows areas of ileum that appear to be thickened (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows the typical trifoliate appearance of a strictureplasty (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f23a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f23b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g23b.jpeg" height="1305" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f23b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> Strictureplasty. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows areas of ileum that appear to be thickened (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows the typical trifoliate appearance of a strictureplasty (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f23b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g02a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1078" aria-labelledby="f2a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Intestinal fold abnormalities. <b>(a)</b> Coronal HASTE MR image (1280/86, 150° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows thickening and distortion of the mucosal folds of the distal and terminal ileum (arrows), as well as polypoid changes (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution coronal HASTE MR image (1280/86, 150° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness), in a section parallel to the terminal ileum, shows an area of high signal intensity within the thickened folds (arrow), a finding suggestive of edema. <b>(c)</b> Image obtained at colonoscopy shows the ulcerated, edematous terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f2a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g02b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1278" aria-labelledby="f2b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Intestinal fold abnormalities. <b>(a)</b> Coronal HASTE MR image (1280/86, 150° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows thickening and distortion of the mucosal folds of the distal and terminal ileum (arrows), as well as polypoid changes (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution coronal HASTE MR image (1280/86, 150° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness), in a section parallel to the terminal ileum, shows an area of high signal intensity within the thickened folds (arrow), a finding suggestive of edema. <b>(c)</b> Image obtained at colonoscopy shows the ulcerated, edematous terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f2b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2c-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c02c.jpeg" height="910" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f2c-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Intestinal fold abnormalities. <b>(a)</b> Coronal HASTE MR image (1280/86, 150° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows thickening and distortion of the mucosal folds of the distal and terminal ileum (arrows), as well as polypoid changes (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution coronal HASTE MR image (1280/86, 150° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness), in a section parallel to the terminal ileum, shows an area of high signal intensity within the thickened folds (arrow), a finding suggestive of edema. <b>(c)</b> Image obtained at colonoscopy shows the ulcerated, edematous terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f2c-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g03a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1734" aria-labelledby="f3a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Fissuring ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) of the ileum shows marked bowel wall thickening. Early fissuring ulcers are seen as disruptions in the mucosal lining (arrowhead); deeper ulcers (straight arrows) produce nodular and asymmetric bowel wall thickening (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×10; hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows confluent areas of mucosal breakdown (arrows), thickening of the bowel wall, and fissuring ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f3a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c03b.jpeg" height="936" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f3b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Fissuring ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) of the ileum shows marked bowel wall thickening. Early fissuring ulcers are seen as disruptions in the mucosal lining (arrowhead); deeper ulcers (straight arrows) produce nodular and asymmetric bowel wall thickening (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×10; hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows confluent areas of mucosal breakdown (arrows), thickening of the bowel wall, and fissuring ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f3b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g04a.jpeg" height="842" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Transmural ulcers and pseudopolyps. <b>(a)</b> Axial true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows nonspecific thickening of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial HASTE MR image (1280/90, 150° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat saturation shows a deep transmural ulcer (arrow) with inflammation and edema extending into the extraintestinal space. <b>(c)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows thickened, inflamed bowel with a polypoid appearance due to residual mucosal islands (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the ulcerated mucosa with pseudopolyps.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f4a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g04b.jpeg" height="969" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Transmural ulcers and pseudopolyps. <b>(a)</b> Axial true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows nonspecific thickening of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial HASTE MR image (1280/90, 150° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat saturation shows a deep transmural ulcer (arrow) with inflammation and edema extending into the extraintestinal space. <b>(c)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows thickened, inflamed bowel with a polypoid appearance due to residual mucosal islands (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the ulcerated mucosa with pseudopolyps.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f4b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4c-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g04c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1200" aria-labelledby="f4c-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Transmural ulcers and pseudopolyps. <b>(a)</b> Axial true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows nonspecific thickening of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial HASTE MR image (1280/90, 150° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat saturation shows a deep transmural ulcer (arrow) with inflammation and edema extending into the extraintestinal space. <b>(c)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows thickened, inflamed bowel with a polypoid appearance due to residual mucosal islands (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the ulcerated mucosa with pseudopolyps.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f4c-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4d-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c04d.jpeg" height="657" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f4d-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> Transmural ulcers and pseudopolyps. <b>(a)</b> Axial true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows nonspecific thickening of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial HASTE MR image (1280/90, 150° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat saturation shows a deep transmural ulcer (arrow) with inflammation and edema extending into the extraintestinal space. <b>(c)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows thickened, inflamed bowel with a polypoid appearance due to residual mucosal islands (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the ulcerated mucosa with pseudopolyps.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f4d-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g05a.jpeg" height="1414" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Transmural ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows deep transmural ulcers as linear spiculated areas of hyperintensity (arrowhead). Fat hypertrophy is seen around the inflamed bowel (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution axial true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in the same segment as in <b>a</b>, shows transmural ulcers (arrowhead). Early fistulation also is seen (arrows), a finding that prompted a change in medical treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f5a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g05b.jpeg" height="1513" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Transmural ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows deep transmural ulcers as linear spiculated areas of hyperintensity (arrowhead). Fat hypertrophy is seen around the inflamed bowel (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> High-resolution axial true FISP MR image (3.8/1.6, 60° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in the same segment as in <b>a</b>, shows transmural ulcers (arrowhead). Early fistulation also is seen (arrows), a finding that prompted a change in medical treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f5b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g06a.jpeg" height="1312" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Linear ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Thin-section axial HASTE MR image obtained with fat suppression shows an area of intramural hyperintensity (straight arrow) parallel to the lumen (curved arrow), a finding suggestive of linear ulceration. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.3/2.4, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in the same segment as in <b>a</b>, shows a longitudinal striate pattern of enhancement (arrow), a finding suggestive of linear ulcerations, which are pathognomonic for Crohn disease. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows linear ulcers (arrow). Edematous mucosal folds along the line of ulcers are responsible for the linear filling defects and enhancement seen on MR images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f6a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g06b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1203" aria-labelledby="f6b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Linear ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Thin-section axial HASTE MR image obtained with fat suppression shows an area of intramural hyperintensity (straight arrow) parallel to the lumen (curved arrow), a finding suggestive of linear ulceration. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.3/2.4, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in the same segment as in <b>a</b>, shows a longitudinal striate pattern of enhancement (arrow), a finding suggestive of linear ulcerations, which are pathognomonic for Crohn disease. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows linear ulcers (arrow). Edematous mucosal folds along the line of ulcers are responsible for the linear filling defects and enhancement seen on MR images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f6b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6c-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c06c.jpeg" height="744" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f6c-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Linear ulcers. <b>(a)</b> Thin-section axial HASTE MR image obtained with fat suppression shows an area of intramural hyperintensity (straight arrow) parallel to the lumen (curved arrow), a finding suggestive of linear ulceration. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.3/2.4, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in the same segment as in <b>a</b>, shows a longitudinal striate pattern of enhancement (arrow), a finding suggestive of linear ulcerations, which are pathognomonic for Crohn disease. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows linear ulcers (arrow). Edematous mucosal folds along the line of ulcers are responsible for the linear filling defects and enhancement seen on MR images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f6c-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g07a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1306" aria-labelledby="f7a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Cobblestoned appearance of bowel. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows thickened terminal ileum (arrow) and cecum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in a plane parallel to the terminal ileum, shows abnormally oriented and thickened mucosal folds (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the cobblestoned appearance of edematous mucosa between longitudinal and transverse linear ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f7a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g07b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1283" aria-labelledby="f7b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Cobblestoned appearance of bowel. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows thickened terminal ileum (arrow) and cecum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in a plane parallel to the terminal ileum, shows abnormally oriented and thickened mucosal folds (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the cobblestoned appearance of edematous mucosa between longitudinal and transverse linear ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f7b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7c-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03c07c.jpeg" height="1280" width="877" aria-labelledby="f7c-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Cobblestoned appearance of bowel. <b>(a)</b> Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) shows thickened terminal ileum (arrow) and cecum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal high-resolution true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 80° flip angle, 2-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression, in a plane parallel to the terminal ileum, shows abnormally oriented and thickened mucosal folds (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a resected bowel segment shows the cobblestoned appearance of edematous mucosa between longitudinal and transverse linear ulcers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f7c-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8a-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g08a.jpeg" height="1351" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8a-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Layered enhancement patterns. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.3/2.4, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat saturation shows inflamed terminal ileum with a layered enhancement pattern (arrow) that comprises enhancing mucosa and serosa separated by an edematous submucosal layer. <b>(b)</b> Axial VIBE MR image (5.3/2.4, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat saturation shows the halo sign created by fibrofatty change in chronic Crohn disease (arrow), in which the enhancing mucosa and serosa are separated by a markedly hypointense submucosal layer. Note the lack of mesenteric inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f8a-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8b-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g08b.jpeg" height="1263" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8b-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Layered enhancement patterns. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced VIBE MR image (5.3/2.4, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat saturation shows inflamed terminal ileum with a layered enhancement pattern (arrow) that comprises enhancing mucosa and serosa separated by an edematous submucosal layer. <b>(b)</b> Axial VIBE MR image (5.3/2.4, 10° flip angle, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained with fat saturation shows the halo sign created by fibrofatty change in chronic Crohn disease (arrow), in which the enhancing mucosa and serosa are separated by a markedly hypointense submucosal layer. Note the lack of mesenteric inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f8b-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9-0291847" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095503/asset/images/g09oc03g09x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1219" aria-labelledby="f9-0291847" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> The comb sign. Coronal true FISP MR image (5.7/2.3, 60° flip angle, 4-mm section thickness) obtained with fat suppression shows extensive fat proliferation around in-flamed bowel segments. Engorged mesenteric vessels form the comb sign (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095503&amp;id=f9-0291847">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0291847" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Stange EF, Travis SP, Vermeire S, et al. European evidence based consensus on the diagnosis and management of Crohn’s disease: definitions and diagnosis. <em>Gut</em> 2006;55(suppl 1):i1–i15.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/gut.2005.081950a">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16481628/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=European+evidence+based+consensus+on+the+diagnosis+and+management+of+Crohn%E2%80%99s+disease%3A+definitions+and+diagnosis&amp;author=EF+Stange&amp;author=SP+Travis&amp;author=S+Vermeire&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=Gut&amp;pages=i1-i15&amp;doi=10.1136%2Fgut.2005.081950a&amp;pmid=16481628">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="b2-0291847" 